---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Naman Chetwani"
  description="Personal website for Naman Chetwani."
>
  <main class="page">
    <div class="page-top">
      <nav class="top-nav" aria-label="Primary">
        <a class="nav-link current" href="/">Naman Chetwani</a>
        <a class="nav-link" href="/things-ive-done">Things I've Done</a>
        <a class="nav-link" href="/reading">Reading</a>
      </nav>
      <button class="theme-toggle" type="button" data-theme-toggle aria-label="Switch theme">
        Light mode
      </button>
    </div>

    <article class="essay">
      <h1>hi, i'm Naman</h1>

      <p>I’m 15, I go to Dougherty Valley High School, and I think of myself as an engineer.</p>

      <p>I like coding, building things, physics, philosophy, and reading far outside my lane.</p>

      <p>
        My long-term goal is to build tech that reduces humanity&apos;s existential debt
        <span class="tooltip-wrap">
          <button class="tooltip-trigger" type="button" aria-describedby="existential-debt-tip">
            ?
          </button>
          <span class="tooltip" id="existential-debt-tip" role="tooltip">
            My shorthand for the preventable long-term risk, fragility, and lost future potential
            humanity keeps creating for itself.
          </span>
        </span>
        .
      </p>

      <p>
        AI safety is the issue I care about most. Amor Fati is the philosophy I try to live by.
        Nietzsche is my favorite philosopher. Crocker&apos;s Rules make sense to me because direct
        feedback beats polite fog.
      </p>

      <h2>Some things I think are important:</h2>
      <ul class="plain-list">
        <li>thinking independently</li>
        <li>building elegant technology instead of performative technology</li>
        <li>taking AI risk seriously</li>
        <li>reading things that expand my frame</li>
        <li>becoming excellent through repetition, reflection, and real work</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        My theory is that if I keep improving how I implement advice, identify weakness, and notice
        what actually compounds, I can improve recursively.
      </p>

      <div class="link-grid" aria-label="Site sections">
        <a class="page-card" href="/things-ive-done">
          <span class="page-card-kicker">separate page</span>
          <strong class="page-card-title">Things I&apos;ve Done</strong>
          <span class="page-card-copy">
            Wildfire aircraft, fire modeling, science fair work, competitions, and self-study.
          </span>
        </a>

        <a class="page-card" href="/reading">
          <span class="page-card-kicker">separate page</span>
          <strong class="page-card-title">Reading</strong>
          <span class="page-card-copy">
            Favorite books, essays, channels, and the ideas I keep returning to.
          </span>
        </a>
      </div>

      <p>Breakfast: billions of tokens.</p>
    </article>

    <a
      class="corner-link"
      href="https://github.com/coder-2011"
      target="_blank"
      rel="noreferrer"
    >
      github.com/coder-2011
    </a>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
